</style></head><body dir="ltr" style="max-width:8.5in;margin-top:0.7874in; margin-bottom:0.7874in; margin-left:0.7874in; margin-right:0.7874in; "><h2 class="P34"><a id="a__Introduction"><span/></a>Introduction</h2><p class="P1"><span class="T3">Heat pump is a low carbon solution of heating and cooling </span><span class="T4">in temperate </span><span class="T5">and shore </span><span class="T4">regions.</span><span class="T3">  </span><span class="T2">For brevity, we skip fundamentals of </span><span class="T6">heat pumps</span><span class="T2">. Readers unfamiliar with this topic can </span><span class="T6">watch </span><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=14MmsNPtn6U" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="T7">this video </span></a><span class="T6">for the basics.</span></p><p class="P2">Here I point out how water-to-water <span class="T8">self-contained</span> heat pumps overcome <span class="T9">some</span> disadvantages of air-to-air heat pump that hampers its <span class="T10">adoption</span>.</p><h2 class="P35"><a id="a__Advantages_of_water_to_water"><span/></a>Advantages <span class="T1">of water to water</span></h2><h3 class="P25"><a id="a__Compact__lightweight"><span/></a>Compact, lightweight</h3><p class="P2"> </p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P2"><!--Next '
            div' is a draw:frame.
        --><div style="height:3.4626in;width:6.9252in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0cm; top:0cm; " class="fr4" id="Image2"><img style="height:8.795cm;width:17.59cm;" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"/></div><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">Because of the relatively low thermal capacitance and conductance of air, air-to-air AC and heat pump units need large and heavy <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T11">copper </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T12">coils, </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T11">aluminum </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T12">fins </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T13">and </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T11">noisy </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T14">outside</span><span class="T11"> </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T13">fans</span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T12"> to exchange heat between refrigerant and air. </span></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="P3">The combination of copper, aluminum and moist air accelerates galvanic corrosion of the aluminum fins. </p><p class="P4"> </p><p class="P32"> </p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P33"><!--Next '
            div' is a draw:frame.
        --><div style="height:6.5138in;width:5.1307in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0cm; top:0cm; " class="fr3" id="Image1"><img style="height:16.5451cm;width:13.032cm;" alt="" src="data:image/jpeg;base64,"/></div><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">Picture: an AC outdoor unit with <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T15">most </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">fins <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T16">corroded away</span></div></div></div></div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="P5">Water-to-refrigerant heat exchangers are small and light. They can be made of corrosion resistant metal such as stainless steel.  <span class="T8">Small and light translate to cost savings on </span><span class="T17">shipping</span><span class="T8"> and installation. </span></p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Quiet"><span/></a>Quiet</h3><p class="P6">Compared to condenser fans, water pumps generate much lower audible noise. </p><h3 class="P26"><a id="a__Consumer_installable"><span/></a>Consumer installable</h3><p class="P7">Split AC units have to be installed by certified HVAC technicians. Self-contained AC units are  installable by homeowners and unskilled personnel, reducing professional labor cost. </p><p class="P8"><span class="T18">Water to water</span> heat pump units convey heat or <span class="T18">cool</span> to the rooms with chill or hot circulation water. <span class="T18">Compared to minisplits and central AC, this avoids routing refrigeration lines or air ducts between </span><span class="T18">rooms.  </span><span class="T19">Running </span><span class="T20">low pressure circulation </span><span class="T19">water pipes </span><span class="T21">and finding leaks </span><span class="T22">on them </span><span class="T19">is a much easier task </span><span class="T23">for consumers.</span></p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Propane_as_refrigerant"><span/></a>Propane as refrigerant</h3><p class="P9">Propane<span class="T24">(R290)</span> is a <span class="T25">cheap </span><span class="T26">and </span><span class="T27">ecofriendly</span><span class="T25"> </span>flammable refrigerant with nice refrigeration properties. <span class="T28">Propane is less than $2/kg, compared to R407c and R410a that costs $</span><span class="T29">7</span><span class="T28">-$20 per kg </span><span class="T30">(typical residential systems hold between 2 and 10 kg of refrigerant)</span></p><p class="P9"><span class="T31">It </span><span class="T32">also works </span><span class="T33">the </span><span class="T32">best</span><span class="T31"> with </span><span class="T34">the </span><span class="T31">cheapest </span><span class="T35">type of</span><span class="T31"> </span><span class="T36">lubricant </span><span class="T31">oil -</span><span class="T35"> mineral oil, </span><span class="T37">unlike newer </span>refrigerant<span class="T37">s that requires the </span><span class="T38">more</span><span class="T37"> expensive POE oil.</span></p><p class="P37"><span class="T39">I</span>ts usage in indoor installations <span class="T40">are limited by</span> fire <span class="T41">risk</span> concerns. <span class="T42">Water-to-water heat pumps</span><span class="T43"> eliminate</span><span class="T42"> the risk</span><span class="T43"> b</span><span class="T40">y </span><span class="T44">submerging the</span><span class="T40"> unit </span><span class="T44">in</span><span class="T40"> water </span><span class="T44">and </span><span class="T45">limiting</span><span class="T44"> </span><span class="T45">refrigerant</span><span class="T44"> </span><span class="T46">outside buildings</span><span class="T44">.</span></p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Hard_to_steal"><span/></a>Hard to steal</h3><p class="P42">Thieves don’t like to dive under water to steal a<span class="T114">n underwater</span> <span class="T116">packaged </span><span class="T115">chiller/heater </span>unit <span class="T119">that hardly contains any </span><span class="T122">precious</span><span class="T120"> </span><span class="T119">metal.</span><span class="T117"> </span><span class="T123">T</span><span class="T117">he refrigerant is </span><span class="T118">neither</span><span class="T117"> worth stealing.</span> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__The_water_body"><span/></a>The water body</h2><p class="P10">By putting the outdoor unit in water, we are actually using the water body as a giant heatsink.</p><p class="P11">For places with a natural water body, such as a <span class="T47">pond, r</span><span class="T48">iver</span>, lake or sea, <span class="T49">we don’t need much calculations, just put the unit deep enough to </span><span class="T107">have </span><span class="T49">contact with never freezing water.</span></p><p class="P30">For places without a natural water body, <span class="T50">we need to create an artificial </span><span class="T51">pond or pool,</span><span class="T50"> and fill it with </span><span class="T52">a cheap water source, such as rainwater and graywater.  </span><span class="T53">How to size the volume and surface area of this artificial </span><span class="T51">pond</span><span class="T53">?</span></p><h3 class="P27"><a id="a__Small_water_body_for_the_summer"><span/></a>Small water body<span class="T54"> for the summer</span></h3><p class="P12">It is easier to have a small <span class="T53">artificial </span><span class="T51">pond </span>for summer <span class="T55">cooling</span> than for winter <span class="T55">heating</span>. In summer, the surface area of pond will evaporate, taking out heat <span class="T55">from condenser. </span><span class="T56">During winter, </span><span class="T57">the </span><span class="T58">surface</span><span class="T57"> could freeze when air temperature is below freezing. </span><span class="T59">While it’s easier for a heat pump to extract heat from liquid water, the extraction stops once the </span><span class="T60">small </span><span class="T59">water </span><span class="T61">body </span><span class="T59">freeze </span><span class="T61">into a</span><span class="T60">n</span><span class="T61"> </span><span class="T62">iceberg</span><span class="T61">.</span></p><p class="P13">According to <a href="https://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/evaporation-water-surface-d_690.html" class="Internet_20_link">EngineeringToolbox</a>, </p><h3 class="P29"><a id="a__Evaporation_of_water_from_a_water_surface"><span/></a>Evaporation of water from a water surface</h3><p class="P15">like an open tank, a swimming pool or similar - depends on water temperature, air temperature, air humidity and air velocity above the water surface.</p><p class="P14">The amount of evaporated water can be expressed as:</p><p class="P16">g<span class="T63">s</span> = ΘA(x<span class="T63">s </span>– x) / 3600  : amount of evaporated water per second (kg/s)</p><p class="P16">g<span class="T63">h</span> = ΘA(x<span class="T63">s</span> –x)  : amount of evaporated water per hour (kg/h)</p><p class="P14">where</p><p class="P17">Θ = (25+19v) : evaporation coefficient (kg/m<span class="T67">2</span><span class="T70">h</span>)</p><p class="P14">v: velocity of air above the water surface (m/s)</p><p class="P14">A: water surface area (m<span class="T66">2</span>)</p><p class="P14">x<span class="T63">s</span> : maximum humidity ratio of saturated air at the same temperature as the water surface (kg/kg)  (kg H<span class="T63">2</span>O in kg Dry Air)</p><p class="P18">x: humidity ratio <span class="T76">of</span> air (kg/kg)  (kg H<span class="T63">2</span>O in kg Dry Air)</p><h3 class="P28"><a id="a__Required_Heat_Supply"><span/></a>Required Heat Supply</h3><p class="P14">Most of the heat or energy required for the evaporation is taken from the water itself. To maintain the water temperature, heat must be supplied to the water.</p><p class="P14">Required heat to cover evaporation can be calculated as</p><p class="P14">q = h<span class="T63">we</span> g<span class="T63">s</span> </p><p class="P14">where</p><p class="P19">q = heat supplied (kW, 1 kW = 3412 Btu/h)</p><p class="P14">h<span class="T63">we</span> = evaporation heat of water <span class="T77">at</span><span class="T78"> </span><span class="T77">temperature </span>(kJ/kg)</p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Example__45000_BTU_h_AC_water-cooled_condenser"><span/></a>Example: <span class="T79">45</span>000 BTU/h AC water-cooled condenser</h3><p class="P20"><span class="T80">Crude and conservative a</span><span class="T79">ssum</span><span class="T80">ptions:</span></p><ul><li><p class="P40" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">•.</span><span class="T79">COP=3, making the condenser heat output to </span><span class="T81">45000*(1+1/3) =</span><span class="T79"> 60000BTU/h </span><span class="T82">= 17.6k</span><span class="T83">W</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P39" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">•.</span><span class="T83">Ambient air temperature 40</span><span class="T84">°</span><span class="T83">C (104</span><span class="T84">°</span><span class="T83">F), </span><span class="T86">in which </span><span class="T87">x</span><span class="T64">s </span><span class="T71">= </span><span class="T72">0.04, </span><span class="T73">and relative humidity 50%, making x=0.02</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P41" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">•.</span><span class="T80">M</span><span class="T88">aximum water temperature is 55</span><span class="T85">°</span><span class="T83">C, </span><span class="T89">making enthalpy of evaporation around 2400</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul><p class="P21">Let’s fill in the numbers on<span class="T90">to </span><a href="https://www.engineeringtoolbox.com/evaporation-water-surface-d_690.html" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="T87">EngineeringToolbox</span></a> <span class="T90">webform, </span><span class="T80">to see how large a pool’s surface evaporation could keep water temperature steady.</span></p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P22"><!--Next '
            div' is a draw:frame.
        --><div style="height:3.1327in;width:6.3646in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0cm; top:0cm; " class="fr2" id="Image3"><img style="height:7.9571cm;width:16.1661cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></div><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T91">So… </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">21m<!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T66">2 </span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;"><span class="T70">of water could cool the condenser by evaporation. </span></div></div></div></div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="P23">To put this in context, a metal <span class="T92">15ft/</span><span class="T1">33inch</span><span class="T92"> </span><span class="T93">(16.4m</span><span class="T68">2  </span><span class="T74">area size </span><span class="T75">and 13m</span><span class="T69">3</span><span class="T65">  </span><span class="T75">volume</span><span class="T93">)</span><span class="T92"> </span><span class="T94">diameter </span>frame pool from Walmart <span class="T94">costs $200, </span><span class="T95">and it probably costs </span><span class="T108">similar</span><span class="T95"> to dig a below-</span><span class="T96">ground</span><span class="T95"> pool. </span></p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P23"><!--Next '
            div' is a draw:frame.
        --><div style="height:3.3783in;width:6.3752in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0.1321cm; top:-0.127cm; " class="fr1" id="Image4"><img style="height:8.5809cm;width:16.193cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="P31">We should note <span class="T109">that</span> water consumption <span class="T110">by </span>evaporation is not n<span class="T97">egligible. </span><span class="T98">Around </span><span class="T99">300kg</span><span class="T1">(79 gallon)</span><span class="T100"> of water needs to be replenished </span><span class="T101">every </span><span class="T102">14-hour </span><span class="T99">day </span><span class="T103">this AC is operating </span><span class="T104">in full, </span><span class="T105">thus a rainwater catching system is </span><span class="T106">preferred </span><span class="T111">to using city water.</span></p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Heat_Pumps"><span/></a>Heat Pumps</h3><p class="P24"><span class="T112">The </span><span class="T113">aforementioned</span><span class="T112"> small w</span>ater body obviously cannot be used as a heat pump’s heat source. Water’s fusion heat is 333J/g, 13 ton of water gives out 13000000*333 = 4.329e9 joule = 4.103e6 BTU (68 hours for the 60000 BTU/h heat pump) before it all freezes up into a giant block of ice. We cannot replenish water of a frozen pool.</p><p class="P24">However, anywhere adjacent to a large body of water, such as river or lake, have no problem pumping out heat from it. Because water’s density is maximized at 4<span class="T85">°</span><span class="T83">C,</span> water colder than 4<span class="T85">°</span><span class="T83">C </span>will convection up to the surface, where it could freeze into ice, rather than down. Thus, a well designed heat pump heat exchanger deep below surface will not freeze up on itself.</p></body></html>

