</style></head><body dir="ltr" style="max-width:8.5in;margin-top:1in; margin-bottom:1in; margin-left:1in; margin-right:1in; "><p class="P10"> </p><div class="Standard"/>
<p>Comments from 2022: performance enhancement of embedded processors and ubiquitous cellular connectivity have eliminated the need of decentralized channel contention, because the optimal channel assignments can be computed on a single head node or a cloud server. The interference matrix, bandwidth-SINR abstraction and bandwidth utility models are still valid. I archive my CFL algorithm variants in my little museum at <a href="https://github.com/ligonliu/cfl-variants/">repo</a> </p>
<p class="Standard">I classify the current investigated problems in dynamic wireless channel allocation into two relatively independent layers. </p><p class="Standard">In the bottom is the topological layer, which abstracts physical constraints of channel sharing; in the middle exists the utility (or pricing) layer, which abstracts users’ benefit in using the channels.</p><h1 class="Heading_20_1"><a id="a__Abstract"><span/></a>Abstract</h1><p class="Standard">The following models, problems and approaches are proposed:</p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__Topological_Layer_"><span/></a>Topological Layer:</h3><p class="Standard">Fractional channel: Wireless channel is divisible to an extent.</p><p class="Standard">Interference-tolerant channel: Channel’s bandwidth can adapt to SINR by adjusting encoding </p><p class="Standard">Send/Receive asymmetric channel: Send and receive is considered separately </p><h3 class="P3"><a id="a__Utility_Layer_"><span/></a>Utility Layer:</h3><p class="Standard">Concave utility function</p><p class="Standard">Minimal bandwidth &amp; additional utility bandwidth Dualism</p><p class="Standard">Minimal bandwidth channel allocation, based on fractional graph coloring algorithm</p><p class="Standard">Additional utility channel allocation, based on Maximum Marginal Utility Independent Set</p><h1 class="Heading_20_1"><a id="a__Topological_Layer"><span/></a>Topological Layer</h1><p class="Standard">Different models exist in the topological layer. The most widely researched is the simplest model, which can be referred as “0-1 interference”. This model assumes:</p><ul><li><p class="P5" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_10" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;"></span>Two nodes are either interfering or not interfering with each other, if they both transmit or receive in the same channel. <span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P5" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_10" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;"></span>The number of atomic, non-dividable channels is limited.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul><p class="Standard">The 0-1 interference can be modeled with simple graph coloring and maximum independent set problem. </p><p class="Standard">In the real world, some exceptions happen beyond 0-1 interference, like the hidden node and exposed node problem, but I am not trying to amend the model for these exceptions.</p><div class="Standard"> </div><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Fractional_channel_model_improvement_over_non-dividable_channel_"><span/></a>Fractional channel model(improvement over non-dividable channel)</h2><p class="Standard">In the real world, efficient methods to divide and share channel exists in the form of FD,TD and CD MA. Multi-subcarrier baseband and RF is prevalent among communication devices ever since the DSL modem, such that a device can use multiple fractional channels simultaneously.</p><p class="Standard">The benefit of fractional channel is very clear: it allows using less total spectrum to provide same bandwidth for users. Also, as a relaxation, fractional graph coloring problem is easier to solve than integer graph coloring problem.</p><p class="P9"> </p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P9"><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:2.4272in;width:3.0091in; padding:0; " class="fr2" id="Picture_14"><img style="height:6.1651cm;width:7.6431cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="P9">Consider example <span class="T8">of</span> <span class="T8">t</span>he pentagon graph:</p><p class="Standard">If 1 non-dividable 10MHz channel is required by each node, the interference graph need 30MHz spectrum to fulfill the 5 nodes; However, if channels can be fractured by 2, Which means, each node need two 5MHz channels, the interference graph only need 25MHz spectrum. </p><p class="Standard">The difference is in the latter graph, for at least one node, the 10MHz are not continuous. (two separate 5MHz channels)</p><p class="Standard"/><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Shannon-Hartley_theorem_and_interference_tolerance__improvement_over_0_1_"><span/></a>Shannon-Hartley theorem and interference tolerance (improvement over 0/1)</h2><p class="Standard">The basic simplest model considers interference to be binary, either existing or not. In real world, interference is aggregated from different interference sources.</p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="Standard"><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">As the Shannon-Hartley theorem  </div><!--Next '
