</tr><tr class="Table11"><td style="text-align:left;width:0.3222in; " class="Table1_A1"><p class="P6">25</p></td><td style="text-align:left;width:0.3222in; " class="Table1_A1"><p class="P6">18</p></td><td style="text-align:left;width:0.3222in; " class="Table1_A1"><p class="P6">20</p></td><td style="text-align:left;width:0.3215in; " class="Table1_A1"><p class="P6"> </p></td></tr></table><p class="Standard">This matrix must satisfy triangle law, which is: Attenuation(A,C) ≤ Attenuation(A,B) + Attenuation(B,C).</p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="Standard"><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">If two nodes completely cannot hear each other, the attenuation is </div><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline">
       <mrow>
         <mi>−</mi>
         <mi>∞</mi>
        </mrow>
      </math> </span>  <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">.</div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="Standard">A<span class="T5">ij</span> is in dB and measurement of attenuation is supported by most of modern BB/RF chipsets.</p><p class="Standard"/><p class="Standard">Note:</p><p class="P7">The Shannon-Hartley theorem has interesting indications that there is an optimal balance between spectrum availability and SINR. This balance is again ignored by graph coloring modeling. SINR decrease by 3db when interference energy is doubled. In a high SINR system, the bandwidth increase brought by SINR doubling is marginal where in a low SINR system the bandwidth increase brought by SINR doubling can be very significant. SINR is a marginal benefit decreasing resource here.</p><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Send_Receive_asymmetry"><span/></a>Send/Receive asymmetry</h2><p class="Standard">In wireless network, different interference patterns exists for sending and receiving, assuming sending and receiving is on different channels. It creates hidden node and exposed node problem, when graph coloring model treat send interference and receive interference in the same, unit graph way.</p><p class="Standard">The way to exploit this asymmetry is creating two different entities: send (uplink) and receive (downlink) bandwidth. The attenuation matrix remains the same. The utility function (mentioned below) would become a two variable function util(b<span class="T5">s</span> ,b<span class="T5">r</span>), b<span class="T5">s</span>  is send bandwidth, b<span class="T5">r</span>  is receive bandwidth) instead of single variable function util(b).</p><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Conclusion_of_topological_layer_"><span/></a>Conclusion of topological layer:</h2><p class="Standard">Considering the factors mentioned above, the proposed topological model of n nodes consists of:</p><ol><li><p class="P4" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_1" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">(1)</span>Attenuation Matrix A<span class="T5">ij</span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="List_20_Paragraph">Signal attenuation, FROM node i TO node j. Usually A<span class="T5">ij</span>=A<span class="T5">ji</span>, because waves propagate in symmetry in both directions.</p><ol><li><div class="P4" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_1" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">(2)</span>The channel bandwidth constant, b<span class="T5">0</span> in bandwidth equation: <!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
