      </math> </span> <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:-1.27cm;">is a concave function <!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:-1.27cm;"><span class="T6">(“decreasing marginal utility”)</span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:-1.27cm;"><span class="T7">[3]</span></div></div></div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Minimal_bandwidth_channel_allocation__based_on_fractional_graph_coloring_algorithm"><span/></a>Minimal bandwidth channel allocation, based on fractional graph coloring algorithm</h2><p class="Standard">This is already solved by a decentralized iterative randomized algorithm called MultiCFL, which I invented based on the idea of CFL algorithm. </p><p class="Standard">MultiCFL is for fractionally coloring a graph. Each node just sense surrounding interference and change its channel accordingly, there is no need of intercommunication among nodes.</p><p class="Standard">We still need to investigate MultiCFL’s speed (sensing cycles) of convergence, as each MultiCFL cycle need a sensing operation, which can be slow and energy costly.</p><p class="Standard">There exist other centralized algorithms, which is another direction to explore.</p><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Algorithm_for_Extra_Utility_channel_allocation__based_on_Maximum_Weight_Independent_Set"><span/></a>Algorithm for Extra Utility channel allocation, based on Maximum Weight Independent Set</h2><p class="Standard">MultiCFL has only solved the welfare bandwidth allocation problem. However, it also helps solve the extra utility bandwidth problem by providing an approximate fractional coloring of conflict graph.</p><p class="Standard">Fractional graph coloring can also be solved in a greedy manner by incrementally coloring the graph’s maximum independent set with a new color. </p><p class="Standard">In our case with utility, we are trying to find a maximum weight (each node’s weight is its marginal utility) independent set. Finding maximum independent set on unit disk graph is polynomial time solvable.<span class="T7">[5]</span> We want to see if the efficient algorithm can be extended into the case every node has a weight. Also, we want to see if there is efficient decentralized algorithm for finding maximum weight independent set on more general graphs.</p><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Conclusion_of_Utility_Layer"><span/></a>Conclusion of Utility Layer</h2><p class="Standard">The proposed utility function is 0 when bandwidth is less than minimal, and concave up from a minimal bandwidth. Allocation of minimal bandwidth can be solved with fractional graph coloring algorithm, while efficient allocation of additional bandwidth can be modeled with maximum weight independent set problem. </p><p class="Standard">Remember, all those analyses are based on the basic 0-1 unidirectional interference model. The analysis should be extended to the models proposed in the topological part of this article.</p></body></html>

brief reading note of LEACH/HEED for cluster head election, and Leith&Clifford/CFL algorithms of distributed graph coloring for channel allocation

