</style></head><body dir="ltr" style="max-width:8.5in;margin-top:1in; margin-bottom:1in; margin-left:1.25in; margin-right:1.25in; "><p class="P4">In wireless sensor network<span class="T5">s</span>, <span class="T5">c</span>lustering is a common approach to simplify routing and reduce energy consumption. A temporary <span class="T5">cluster head</span>(CH) is usually generated in the cluster to serve tasks traditionally accomplished by base station or access point. </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Scenarios_and_network_structure"><span/></a>Scenarios and network structure</h2><p class="Standard">There are different scenarios where the sensor network is operated, resulting in different optimal strategies. Scenarios might happen that networks nodes are fixed or mobile, energy constraint or energy abundant, and the pattern of data flow are different among networks.</p><p class="P3">Moving node add to the complexity of clustering. The structure must react accordingly to the change of inter-node connectivity. Data might be continuously or intermittently generated from the networks. There may be nodes which aggregate continuous information from other node, do analysis and generate a batch transmission to be received by upper level.</p><p class="P3">The scenario that is earliest and most frequently studied is fixed sensor network, all nodes are with energy constraint, and data flow is “aggregation” based, where sensor nodes do not need sensed data among themselves instead send them to a command center in or outside the network. In this case, CH suffers from battery drain, because it has to use transmission power to route packets from all other nodes in the cluster. The solution is usually making all nodes in the cluster take turns to be the CH.</p><p class="P3">There can be mesh or hierarchical structures among CHs. In hierarchical structure, communication between two CHs is via an upper layer; In mesh structure, communication between two CHs are routed ad-hoc. [2]</p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="P3"><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:1.6693in;width:2.7217in; padding:0; " class="fr4" id="Picture_1"><img style="height:4.24cm;width:6.9131cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:1.6673in;width:2.5756in; padding:0; " class="fr3" id="Picture_2"><img style="height:4.2349cm;width:6.542cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:-6.9131cm;">[2]</div><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:1.6673in;width:2.5756in; padding:0; " class="fr3" id="Picture_2"><img style="height:4.2349cm;width:6.542cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span><!--Next 'div' added for floating.--><div style="display:inline; position:relative; left:0cm;">[2]</div></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Typical_Algorithms"><span/></a><span class="T5">Typical </span>Algorithms</h2><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__LEACH"><span/></a>LEACH</h3><p class="Standard">LEACH<span class="T1">[1]</span> is an important traditional algorithm invented in year 2000. It was invented against the claim that “minimum transmission energy” (MTE) protocols made. Instead of their original claim for minimized the total transmission energy, the total energy consumption in multi-hopping message might even be higher than infrastructure network. It argues, if MTE routing is employed for power constrained device, the device closest to base station will exhaust its battery sooner and die early, resulting in uneven battery life of all the nodes, creating functional problem of the network.</p><p class="Standard">In LEACH, nodes make autonomous decisions without any centralized control. Initially a node randomly decides to be or not to be a CH with probability p or (1-p). If the node decides to be CH, it broadcasts its decision. Each node deciding non-CH selects its cluster by choosing the CH closest to it measured by least transmission energy.</p><p class="Standard">The role of CH is rotated periodically among the nodes. In each rotation phase, each node chooses a random number between 0 and 1 to become CH or not. Of course, the number of nodes deciding to be CH in each area or existing cluster follows Poisson distribution, so there will be fluctuates in configuration. <a id="_GoBack"/></p><p class="Standard">The problems with the original LEACH algorithm, for example, the probability of becoming a CH is fixed rather than decided considering link availability(to BS and other nodes) and battery status, which would occasionally drain battery. Also, the densities of CHs are not guaranteed to be evenly distributed.<span class="T1">[2]</span></p><h3 class="Heading_20_3"><a id="a__HEED"><span/></a>HEED</h3><p class="Standard">HEED (Hybrid Energy-Efficient Distributed clustering) was invented in 2004, addressing the need for rotating cluster role for battery power conservation. </p><p class="Standard">HEED has three phases of execution[2]:</p><ol><li><p class="P5" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_28" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">1.</span>Initialization:<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="List_20_Paragraph">Every node discovers their neighbors within the cluster range. </p><p class="List_20_Paragraph">Every node compute its own initial CH probability CH<span class="T2">prob</span> = max(f(E<span class="T2">r</span>/E<span class="T2">max</span>), p_min), where E<span class="T2">r</span> is residual energy, and E<span class="T2">max</span> is maximum energy, p_min is the parameter (minimum probability) set for fast convergence.</p><ol><li><p class="P5" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_28" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">2.</span>Main processing:<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="List_20_Paragraph">Repeat{</p><p class="P1">For any node v in the network,</p><p class="P1">If v received some CH messages, choose one head with minimum cost</p><p class="P2">If v does not have a CH, elect itself to become a CHwith CH<span class="T2">prob</span>.</p><p class="P1">CH<span class="T2">prob</span> <span class="T3"></span> min(CH<span class="T2">prob</span> * 2, 1)</p><p class="List_20_Paragraph">}</p><p class="List_20_Paragraph">until CHprob = 1</p><ol><li><p class="P5" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_28" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">3.</span>Finalization:<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="List_20_Paragraph">for each node:</p><p class="P2">If CH is found, join its cluster</p><p class="P2">Otherwise, elect itself to be CH</p><p class="List_20_Paragraph"> </p><p class="Standard">HEED has the following advantages: </p><ol><li><p class="P6" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_37" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">1.</span>Converge in almost constant O(1) iterations. According to the original paper’s analysis, the worst case is when a node has very low energy left, which node will start executing HEED with CH<span class="T2">prob</span> set to p<span class="T2">min</span>. However, CH<span class="T2">prob</span> doubles in every step, and phase II of the protocol terminates one step (iteration) after CH<span class="T2">prob</span> reaches 1.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><p class="List_20_Paragraph">As a result, it derives:</p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="List_20_Paragraph"><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:0.5126in;width:1.7917in; padding:0; " class="fr1" id="Picture_4"><img style="height:1.302cm;width:4.5509cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><ol><li><p class="P6" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_37" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">2.</span>Message overhead is O(1) per node. “During the execution of HEED, a tentative CH generates at most N<span class="T2">iter</span> CH messages (O(1)). A regular node is silent until it sends one join message to a CH.”[2] So there are no more than N join messages in the network, Thus, the message exchanged in the clusterhead selection process is no more than N<span class="T2">iter</span> *N = O(N).<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P6" style="margin-left:1.27cm;"><span class="ListLabel_20_37" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">3.</span>CHs are well distributed in HEED: The probability for two clusterheads to be within the same cluster range is:<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ol><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="List_20_Paragraph"><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:0.5598in;width:2.0311in; padding:0; " class="fr1" id="Picture_5"><img style="height:1.4219cm;width:5.159cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="Standard">Comparisons with LEACH:</p><p class="Standard">The HEED authors did some simulation on HEED and a modified version of LEACH, and find out that HEED has superior performance in aspects of Network lifetime, Ratio of energy used in clustering in total energy consumption and Network lifetime for a 500-node network as the sink travels farther. </p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="Standard"><!--Next '
            div' is a draw:frame.
        --><div style="height:1.4374in;width:2.8161in; padding:0;  float:left; position:relative; left:0.0259cm; top:4.824cm; " class="fr2" id="Picture_8"><img style="height:3.651cm;width:7.1529cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></div><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
