            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:1.7291in;width:2.9709in; padding:0; " class="fr1" id="Picture_7"><img style="height:4.3919cm;width:7.5461cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:1.7291in;width:2.9709in; padding:0; " class="fr1" id="Picture_7"><img style="height:4.3919cm;width:7.5461cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="Standard">Those three graphs are from the HEED paper. They find out HEED’s min degree variant and max degree variant has similar performance in network lifetime and energy consumption, while both is higher performance compared to the LEACH algorithm they are benchmarking with.</p><p class="Standard"> </p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Comments"><span/></a>Comments</h2><p class="Standard">The LEACH and HEED are typical algorithms used in CH selection, independently without routing protocol. They solve the data aggregation problem in simple and decentralized manner, minimized message exchange between nodes and maintained computational cost as low as log or constant.</p><p class="Standard">Further research could direct into modeling time sequence of data aggregation, and see if optimizing schedule of messages can provide even lower battery power consumption. Also, mesh-like multi-hop transmission can be investigated, <span class="T4">as an alternative to agglomerative protocols.</span></p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__References"><span/></a>References</h2><p class="Standard">[1] Low energy adaptive clustering hierarchy with deterministic cluster-head selection, (<a href="http://www.vs.inf.ethz.ch/publ/se/IEEE_MWCN2002.pdf" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">http://www.vs.inf.ethz.ch/publ/se/IEEE_MWCN2002.pdf</span></a>, <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/zhendong/leachprotocol" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">http://www.slideshare.net/zhendong/leachprotocol</span></a>)</p><p class="Standard">[2] Distributed Clustering in Ad-hoc Sensor Networks: A Hybrid, Energy-Efficient Approach (<a href="http://www.csee.umbc.edu/~younis/Sensor_Networks/Student_Presentation/Piyush_Shah.pdf" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">http://www.csee.umbc.edu/~younis/Sensor_Networks/Student_Presentation/Piyush_Shah.pdf</span></a>, <a href="http://edge.cs.drexel.edu/regli/Classes/CS680/Papers/heed.pdf" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">http://edge.cs.drexel.edu/regli/Classes/CS680/Papers/heed.pdf</span></a>)</p><p class="Standard"> </p>


        <h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Leith_and_Clifford’s_algorithm"><span/></a><a href="http://www.hamilton.ie/peterc/downloads/rawnet06.pdf" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">Leith and Clifford’s algorithm <br/></span></a></h2><p class="P2">quoted from original <span class="T10">document</span>:</p><p class="Standard">“</p><p class="Standard">1) Initialize p = [1/c, 1/c, . . ., 1/c]<span class="T2">T</span></p><p class="Standard">2) Toss a weighted coin to select a channel, with p<span class="T4">i</span></p><p class="Standard">The probability of selecting channel i. Measure the quality of the channel: any interference measure can be used that yields a “success” when interference/channel noise is within acceptable levels and “failure” otherwise. Thus, we might, for example, use an aggregate measure derived from multiple packet transmissions, direct measurement of the channel SNR or some other approach.</p><p class="Standard">3) On success on channel i, update p as</p><p class="Standard">p<span class="T4">i</span> = 1 (1)</p><p class="Standard">p<span class="T4">j</span> = 0, <span class="T6">∀</span>j ≠ i (2)</p><p class="Standard">i.e. on success we stay with that channel. This creates a degree of “stickiness” which ensures that any channel allocation that removes interference between WLANs is an absorbing state.</p><p class="Standard">4) On failure on channel i, update p as</p><p class="Standard">p<span class="T4">i</span> = (1 − b) p<span class="T4">i</span> (3)</p><p class="Standard">p<span class="T4">j</span> = (1 − b) p<span class="T4">j</span> + b/(c − 1), <span class="T6">∀</span>j ≠  i (4)</p><p class="Standard">i.e. on a failed transmission, <span class="T10">exponentially</span> decrease the probability of using that channel, redistributing the probability evenly across the other channels. b is a design parameter, 0 &lt; b &lt; 1; the selection of the value of b is considered in detail in the next section.</p><p class="Standard">5) Return to 2).</p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__CFL_algorithm"><span/></a><a href="http://www.hamilton.ie/ken_duffy/Downloads/cfl.pdf" class="Internet_20_link"><span class="Internet_20_link">CFL algorithm</span></a></h2><p class="Standard"><span class="T7">“The CFL algorithm is parameterized by β </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> (0, 1) and works as follows. Time t </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> {0, 1, . . .} is discrete and at each instant every node n </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> 1, . . . , N in the graph selects its color c</span><span class="T5">n</span><span class="T7">(t) according to its own probability distribution p</span><span class="T5">n</span><span class="T7">(t) on the range of available colors {1, . . . , C}. At t = 0, each </span><span class="T7">node’s color distribution is initialized to be the uniform distribution: p</span><span class="T5">n</span><span class="T7"> (0) = (1/C, . . . , 1/C) for all n </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> {1, . . . , N}. The distributions p</span><span class="T5">n</span><span class="T7"> (t) then evolve for t ≥ 1 according to the following rule:</span></p><!--Next 'div' was a 'text:p'.--><div class="Standard"><!--Next '
            span' is a draw:frame.
        --><span style="height:0.789in;width:5.5846in; padding:0; " class="fr1" id="Picture_4"><img style="height:2.0041cm;width:14.1849cm;" alt="" src="data:image/png;base64,"/></span></div><div style="clear:both; line-height:0; width:0; height:0; margin:0; padding:0;"> </div><p class="Standard"><span class="T7">where δ</span><span class="T5">i</span><span class="T7"> denotes the distribution with unit mass on i </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> {1, . . . , C} and </span><span class="T9">¯</span><span class="T7">δ</span><span class="T5">i</span><span class="T7"> denotes the vector in R</span><span class="T3">C</span><span class="T7"> which has component 0 at i and 1 at all other positions. Let X(t) = (p</span><span class="T5">1</span><span class="T7">(t), . . . , p</span><span class="T5">N</span><span class="T7"> (t)) </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> [0, 1]</span><span class="T3">NC</span><span class="T7">. By construction the sequence {X(t), t </span><span class="T6">∈</span><span class="T7"> {0, 1, . . .}} forms a Markov chain.“</span></p><h2 class="Heading_20_2"><a id="a__Application_in_computer_networks"><span/></a>Application in <span class="T10">computer</span> networks</h2><ul><li><p class="P3" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">•</span>Wavelength assignment in optical-fiber network (where route has been determined) is a graph coloring problem.<span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li><li><p class="P3" style="margin-left:0cm;"><span class="Bullet_20_Symbols" style="display:block;float:left;min-width:0cm;">•</span><span class="T7">When there is </span><span class="T8">additional capacity demand</span><span class="T7">, coloring algorithm is used to allocate </span><span class="T8">additional</span><span class="T7"> channels to one cell. </span><span class="odfLiEnd"/> </p></li></ul></body>





